This is who I was at the very beginning.
My pattern of behavior has always been driven by a salvation fantasy:
I set an enormous goal → treat it as the ultimate solution to all my problems in life—proving myself, escaping my family, gaining freedom → become unable to start because the goal is too overwhelming → fall into anxiety and self-blame → numb myself with procrastination and instant pleasures like shopping and novels → doubt myself even more → need an even bigger goal to prove my worth.

It’s an absolutely terrible cycle. It drains almost all my mental energy, leaving me stuck in either fear of the future or regret about the past, but never able to live in the present.

Back then, I held that distant goal as a lifeline. I didn’t truly want to go there; I just believed that if I could make it there, everything would be fixed. I used it to escape my powerlessness in the moment: poor grades, a chaotic family, painful relationships. I said I wanted to go, but I couldn’t even finish my vocabulary for the day.
MIT was never a goal. It was a shield, standing between me and the thought that I might really not be good enough.
At that point, my progress was 0%. I was still trapped in the pit of using the future to cover up the present.

Now, I still want to go there, but I no longer use it to escape. I start calculating time, making plans, buying courses, studying on my own, negotiating with teachers.
I have turned that distant goal from a shield into a target — knowing it’s difficult, knowing I might miss, but still practicing every single day.
I also begin to deal with things in the present: forgiving myself, setting boundaries, accepting slowness, accepting that I might not get a 5.

I still use this “promised land” to encourage myself, but I no longer fool myself into thinking everything will be perfect once I arrive. I know there will be new problems there. But I am going anyway.
Now my progress is 65%.
I have moved from using the future to escape the present to using the future to guide the present.

That goal might be MIT, or somewhere else. But it is no longer a shield.
It is a signpost.

I write this down not to prove that I deserve a certain school.
I write it to remember:
I once stood right here, looking into the distance, and then step by step, I made my way to today.

This is not an application essay. This is just a record of someone learning to stand on her own feet.
